{"type":"message","id":"a094e442","parentId":"f6ba0500","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:55:29.960Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_wjfcimjw2foy_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 115501\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: experiments/cfi_compression_experiment.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLooking at the goals and recent activity, I see:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 and Phase 1 are marked COMPLETE\r\n2. CFI Analysis was just completed (2026-03-24)\r\n3. Key pending items include:\r\n   - CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n   - CFI filtering implementation\r\n   - Distinguishing \"constant format\" vs \"research trajectory\"\r\n   - Wire Breakaway to TemporalAttention backend\r\n   - Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe CFI_RESULTS.md document showed that only 5.7% of invariants have high CFI (>=0.7), meaning most of what was captured as \"frequent\" is actually noise/metaprogramming artifacts.\r\n\r\nThe natural next step is to run the CFI-weighted compression experiment that was flagged as \"Next\" in the Phase 1 Advancement section. This would compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nI should create a concrete experiment script or document that:\r\n1. Takes the CFI analysis results\r\n2. Implements a CFI-weighted compression approach\r\n3. Compares it against the frequency baseline\r\n4. Measures which approach better predicts next-pulse content\r\n\r\nLet me write a focused experiment design file that can be executed.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 94.3% of frequency-invariants are noise (CFI<0.7), meaning frequency-based compression is mostly signal loss. A CFI-weighted compression experiment is the natural next step to validate this finding.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a CFI-weighted compression experiment that compares CFI-threshold filtering against frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction, using the existing frequency invariant data from CFI_RESULTS.md.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted filtering (keep only CFI>=0.7) will produce better next-pulse prediction than frequency-based filtering (keep only freq>=60), because high-CFI invariants represent true causal structure rather than metaprogramming artifacts.\r\n\r\n## Method\r\n1. Extract invariants from last N pulses\r\n2. Apply two filters:\r\n   - **Baseline:** Frequency filter (freq >= 60)\r\n   - **CFI-weighted:** CFI filter (CFI >= 0.7)\r\n3. Compress current pulse using each invariant set\r\n4. Score each compressed version by overlap with actual next pulse\r\n5. Compare reconstruction quality\r\n\r\n## Metrics\r\n- Token reduction ratio\r\n- Prediction overlap score\r\n- Semantic coherence (LLM-judged)\r\n\r\n## Data Sources\r\n- `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` - CFI analysis with all 10,000+ invariants\r\n- `research/FREQUENCY_INVARIANTS.md` - Frequency baseline data\r\n- `pulse_*.md` - Historical pulse records\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted should achieve ~same compression but BETTER prediction, proving that CFI is the right filter.\r\n```\r\n\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:55:22\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774367729958}}
